&quot;Olga has a great gift for filming with her close team in such a way that we often let ourselves be carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, thanks to which I talked about relatively intimate topics. With my husband, cameraman Jan Malíř, I actually they have become part of our family. We originally wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life anniversary. But since I had another beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot as long as possible. Well, and since I was everywhere in 2019 , my wish was for it to be released in the spring of next year. This documentary film is a thank you to my supporters and everyone who supported and accompanied me in my profession,&quot; says Karel Gott himself about the film.
There are up to sixty times fewer insects than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of all life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is radically shrinking. Another scientific study on this topic came out just this week, and according to it, the situation is even more serious than humanity has realized.
The study is based on field research in a tropical rainforest in Puerto Rico, during which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, there are &quot;ten to sixty times fewer&quot; insects in the rainforest today. It is about the decline of the entire population, i.e. not the number of species, while the research concerned not only insects, but all arthropods. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of other fauna that depends on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, also decreases.
The authors of the research relate their conclusions directly to climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius in the last thirty years, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the author&#39;s team, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously thought.
A large article about the report was published in the Washington Post on Monday, which presents the new findings immediately in the headline as hyperalarming. &quot;It&#39;s one of the most disturbing articles I&#39;ve ever read,&quot; University of Connecticut entomologist David Wagner, whom the paper cites as an independent expert, told the paper.
The extinction of insects also affects Europe. &quot;The decline here is also an order of magnitude,&quot; points out Lukáš Čížek from the Institute of Entomology of the Academy of Sciences. According to him, in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account changes in the landscape, which play a significant role in Europe. &quot;It just runs for a significantly longer time here than in Puerto Rico,&quot; adds Čížek to explain why scientists could measure such a rapid decline in the primeval forest compared to the 1970s.
