&quot;Scary study result.&quot; Islam does not belong to the West, the vast majority of Austrians think
1,200 respondents were interviewed, the survey shows considerable mistrust of Islam in Austrian society.
Almost 60 percent of Austrians fear that some Muslims are terrorists, and 48 percent would demand a ban on the construction of mosques. 80 percent of respondents are in favor of greater monitoring of centers of Islam.
Most Austrians also want Muslims to be restricted in their religious practices, saying that the presence of Muslims sometimes makes them feel like foreigners in their own country.
&quot;The result of the study is frightening,&quot; claims the author of the study, Wolfgang Aschauer, and adds: &quot;Such a tendency towards ethnocentrism could eventually lead to the adoption of discriminatory attitudes. There is a danger that the religious freedoms granted to Muslims will be narrowed.&quot;
The critical attitude is less pronounced among believers. Aschauer claims that in Austria it is not a conflict between religions, but between cultures. According to the sociologist, dialogue and education could help blunt polarization.
According to the study, the most hostile attitudes towards Muslims are held by voters of the extreme right, people without a university education or seniors over 75 years of age. On the other hand, Green voters, people under 30 and university students are the most welcoming.
According to estimates by the Austrian Ministry of the Interior, approximately 700,000 Muslims live in Austria, which has approximately 8.7 million inhabitants. The vast majority have Turkish roots. There are more than 400 Muslim prayer houses and mosques in the country, and Islam has been officially recognized as a religion since 1912.
