Our country has simply not yet been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. It is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, but people with an improving standard of living will also want to have a place to live, to travel in a modern and fast way, to have quality cultural stands, to live without an unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible to complete the inner and outer ring road or to build a high-speed rail or metro to the airport for years. And Prague doesn&#39;t even have a modern, architecturally bold national library, concert hall, or national gallery. The reason is not only the absurd scramble for architectural competitions, spatial plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto &quot;every bolder change is for the worse&quot;.
And when it seems that something more daring could be done, it will almost certainly be thwarted by preservationists or other rather foolish associations or politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding Jan Kaplický&#39;s &quot;blob&quot; designed for the new building of the National Library, President Václav Klaus even wanted to tie himself to the diggers.
However, the list does not end with Prague. The Czech Republic is not able to complete its backbone highway network, nor to start building high-speed train lines, so Germany finally decided to run its tracks for super-fast trains from Berlin to Vienna by a &quot;detour&quot; through Bavaria. In addition, repairs to existing infrastructure are sometimes lost in the slenderian. Getting from Prague to Brno quickly is now a solved puzzle.
Babiš entered politics with the promise that he would &quot;fix things&quot;. In terms of meaningful investments and acceleration of cumbersome bureaucratic procedures, not much has happened yet. Although an amendment to the Act on accelerating the construction of transport infrastructure has been in effect since 2018, we will have to wait for more extensive positive effects, such as easier expropriation of land. And the new construction law, approved by the government, which is supposed to reduce the current average length of the construction procedure from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we&#39;re lucky, start to apply from 2021. But many people probably wouldn&#39;t bet on it .
